                "soldescription": "Image obtained with the Helioseismic and Magnetic Imager (HMI). This instrument studies oscillations of the magnetic field on the solar surface (photosphere), at a wavelength suitable to see the formation of visible sunspots. © NASA / SDO and the AIA, EVE, and HMI science teams.",
                "solinformation": "The Sun is the central star of the Solar System. All other bodies in the Solar System, such as planets, dwarf planets, asteroids, comets and dust, as well as all the satellites associated with them, revolve around the Sun. Responsible for 99.86% of the mass of the Solar System, the Sun has 332 900 times the mass of the Earth, 109 times the diameter of Earth, and 1 300 000 times the volume of our planet.<br>Despite all the other bodies in the Solar System revolving around the Sun, it also revolves around the centre of our galaxy – the Milky Way. The Sun has already completed 20 revolutions since it was formed about 4.6 billion years ago,with each one taking 225 million years.",
                "mercuriodescription": "Mercury’s mosaic, in the visible and near infrared band, obtained by the Messenger probe (NASA). © NASA / Johns Hopkins University Applied Physics Laboratory / Carnegie Institution of Washington.",
                "mercurioinformation": "Despite the similarities with the Moon, Mercury has a much darker surface, because of the graphite dust that covers it. In Mercury the graphite exists in percentages higher than those found on Earth, Mars or the Moon.<br>The most accepted explanation for the presence of this material points out that, 4.5 thousand million years ago, when the planet was still a magma ball, the majority of its minerals crystallized and sunk, while the graphite would have floated to the surface. ",
                "venusdescription": "Radar image of the Venus surface. © NASA / JPL",
                "venusinformation": "When observed in the ultraviolet band, the clouds that completely cover the planet Venus are visible, which prevents direct observation of the planet's surface. Only through radar observations, such as those made by the Magellan spacecraft, was it possible to penetrate this layer of clouds, and reveal the surface<br>Venus' thick atmosphere is responsible for the uncontrolled greenhouse effect, which makes it the hottest planet in the Solar System.", 
                "terradescription": "Composite image of 3 photos taken by the satellite Deep Space Climate Observatory (DSCOVR), from a distance of 1.5 million kilometers from Earth. © NASA",
                "terrainformation": "The Earth is the only Solar System planet with liquid water on the surface, which covers more than 70% of the surface of our planet. However, 97% of the water is salted, and only 3% is freshwater.<br>Of the latter, approximately 69% (or slightly more than 1.7% of the total amount of water in the planet) is in the form of ice, situated in the polar caps and glaciers, whereas 30% is underground.", 
                "luadescription": "This image, based on data from NASA's LRO spacecraft, shows the face of the Moon as we see it from Earth. © NASA/GSFC/Arizona State University",
                "luainformation":"The Moon, our natural satellite, is until now the only celestial body that was ever visited by humans. Seen from Earth, it presents dark spots, known as Mares, which during millennia were thought to be full of liquid water. Actually, Mares are zones composed of basalts, formed by the rapid cooling of lava.<br>Mares are exclusive of the near side of the Moon, and do not exist on the far side.",
                "martedescription": "Mosaic obtained from 102 images of Mars captured by the Viking Orbiter probe at about 2500 kilometers from the planet.  © NASA/JPL-Caltech",
                "marteinformation": "Mars is the home of some of the biggest geological structures of the entire Solar System. The Mariner Valley (Valles Marineris) is a canyon with an approximate length of 3000 kilometers, having some areas with a  depth up to 9 kilometers  and with its margins separated by up to 100 kilometers.<br>The biggest volcanic mountain of the entire solar system is also located on Mars – Olympus Mons has 3 times the elevation of the Everest and its base has an area similar to the area of the entire Iberian Península.", 
                "ceresdescription": "Images in natural colors of Ceres obtained in May of 2015, by the Dawn probe. © National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA) / Jet Propulsion Laboratory (JPL) / California Institute of Technology e Justin Cowart, The Planetary Society",
                "ceresinformation": "Ceres is a dwarf planet that is located at the asteroid belt, between Mars and Jupiter. It was discovered on January 1, 1801 by Giuseppe Piazzi, however it had been predicted by Johann Bode in 1772.<br>Its atmosphere is very tenuous, formed mainly by steam, created from the water that sublimes and leaves the surface. It consists essentially of rock and ice and has many low level craters in its surface. Ceres was the first object to be considered an asteroid. In 2006 together with Pluto, it entered the dwarf planet category, being the smallest of them all.", 
                "jupiterdescription": "Image of Jupiter obtained by the Hubble Space Telescope on April 21, 2014, with the Wide Field Camera 3. © NASA, ESA, and A. Simon (GSFC).",
                "jupiterinformation": "Jupiter is the largest planet of the Solar System, with 11 times the diameter of Earth. Thus, in volume, about 1330 Earths would fit inside Jupiter.<br>This planet is one of the gas giants, with storms that go past 500 km/h. One of the most recognized features of Jupiter is the Great Red Spot, an anticyclone that is more than 300 years old. The planet has more than 75 known moons, the four largest of which were found by Galileo Galilei in 1609.",    
                "saturnodescription": "Mosaic of 30 images of Saturn, obtained by the Cassini spacecraft (NASA). © NASA/JPL/Space Science Institute",
                "saturnoinformation": "Saturn is famous for its rings, but they are not perfect, despite their appearance at first glance. In reality, the rings are made of millions of ice blocks that can measure from a few centimeters to many kilometers. Because the ice reflects the Sunlight very well, in order to watch these rings from planet Earth, we only need an instrument that is capable of zooming in an image around 30 times.<br>This planet is also very light – if Saturn could be placed in a container of water, it would float.", 
                "uranodescription": "Composition of images in the infrared band of the planet Uranus. © Lawrence Sromovsky, University of Wisconsin-Madison/W.M. Keck Observatory",
                "uranoinformation": "Like gas giants, icy giants also have rings, severe storms and hurricanes that, in the case of Uranus, can reach over 1000 km/h. Icy giants have a superior hydrogen atmosphere, which is similar to the ones of gas giants, but their interior is an icy “mantle”.<br>The colour of Uranus is due to the third most abundant component in its atmosphere, the methane ice.", 
                "neptunodescription": "Image of Neptune obtained by the Voyager 2 probe, at over 7 million km from the planet. © NASA/JPL",
                "neptunoinformation": "Neptune is the only planet in the Solar System whose existence was predicted by mathematical calculations, made by Urbain Le Verrier, which guided the German Johann Gottfried Galle to its discovery in 1846.<br>Despite being smaller than Uranus, Neptune is more massive (and therefore more dense) than the latter. It is also in Neptune that we can find the most violent storms in the entire Solar System, with winds that can exceed 2000 km/h.",
 
